00:02:04.838 --> 00:02:08.121
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:09.530 --> 00:02:10.870
RON SIEGEL: Welcome, everybody.

00:02:10.870 --> 00:02:14.067
Thank you, Matt, for inviting
me and for everybody else

00:02:14.067 --> 00:02:15.150
at Google for inviting me.

00:02:15.150 --> 00:02:17.730
Thank you for coming
here in person and those

00:02:17.730 --> 00:02:21.200
of you who have come virtually.

00:02:21.200 --> 00:02:24.880
Usually, we don't choose
to attend a talk like this

00:02:24.880 --> 00:02:27.780
when we've just fallen
in love, won the lottery,

00:02:27.780 --> 00:02:29.560
and gotten a promotion.

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:31.430
Rather, we get interested
in these topics

00:02:31.430 --> 00:02:34.440
either when we've had some kind
of a downturn in our lives,

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:37.040
or maybe our lights are
going OK on the outside,

00:02:37.040 --> 00:02:38.920
but for whatever
reason, we're feeling

00:02:38.920 --> 00:02:42.670
some degree of emotional
distress or difficulty.

00:02:42.670 --> 00:02:45.920
And it turns out
that in recent years,

00:02:45.920 --> 00:02:50.240
neurobiologists, clinical
researchers, and mental health

00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:52.350
professionals have
discovered that a number

00:02:52.350 --> 00:02:54.850
of ancient practices,
mindfulness practice that

00:02:54.850 --> 00:02:57.860
have been refined over the
last 2,500 years or so,

00:02:57.860 --> 00:03:00.980
turned out to be extremely
useful for helping us to work

00:03:00.980 --> 00:03:03.680
with all sorts of everyday
emotional difficulties,

00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:06.030
everything from
anxiety and depression

00:03:06.030 --> 00:03:08.440
to serious difficulties
like chronic pain

00:03:08.440 --> 00:03:11.499
or, perhaps,
relational conflict.

00:03:11.499 --> 00:03:13.790
And in a few minutes, I'm
going to teach you about some

00:03:13.790 --> 00:03:15.900
of those practices
and show you how you

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:17.540
can use them in your own life.

00:03:17.540 --> 00:03:20.010
But in order to use
those effectively,

00:03:20.010 --> 00:03:22.700
it's very, very helpful
to have a sense of,

00:03:22.700 --> 00:03:25.650
how come life is so
difficult for all of us

00:03:25.650 --> 00:03:28.920
in the first place?

00:03:28.920 --> 00:03:31.240
Well, it turns out
that we didn't actually

00:03:31.240 --> 00:03:32.950
evolve to be happy.

00:03:32.950 --> 00:03:35.490
Our brains developed
primarily as organs

00:03:35.490 --> 00:03:37.530
of survival, the same
way the other organs

00:03:37.530 --> 00:03:39.630
in the body developed.

00:03:39.630 --> 00:03:41.710
And to understand this,
it's helpful to look back

00:03:41.710 --> 00:03:45.259
at our past, and let's
start by looking at Lucy.

00:03:45.259 --> 00:03:47.800
This is an artist's conception
of our great great great great

00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:51.750
great great great great great
great et cetera grandmother.

00:03:51.750 --> 00:03:54.127
And she was hanging around
on the African Savannah

00:03:54.127 --> 00:03:56.710
somewhere between three and 1/2
and four and 1/2 million years

00:03:56.710 --> 00:03:57.209
ago.

00:03:57.209 --> 00:03:59.040
There may be an earlier
common ancestor.

00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:00.540
We're not sure.

00:04:00.540 --> 00:04:04.450
And we know that she survived,
because we've got her DNA.

00:04:04.450 --> 00:04:07.310
But how did she possibly
survive out there competing

00:04:07.310 --> 00:04:08.920
with the other wildlife?

00:04:08.920 --> 00:04:11.321
Imagine here coming face
to face with a lion?

00:04:11.321 --> 00:04:12.070
What could she do?

00:04:12.070 --> 00:04:14.280
Well, she could grit her
teeth and bear her claws,

00:04:14.280 --> 00:04:16.240
[GROWLING NOISE]
but that probably

00:04:16.240 --> 00:04:17.790
wouldn't be too effective.

00:04:17.790 --> 00:04:20.079
She might try to rely on
her hide for protection,

00:04:20.079 --> 00:04:21.940
but that's pretty limited.

00:04:21.940 --> 00:04:25.330
Her fur was sillier still.

00:04:25.330 --> 00:04:27.265
She wasn't very fast.

00:04:27.265 --> 00:04:28.890
One of the first
things that you learn,

00:04:28.890 --> 00:04:31.080
if you ever go on a
walking safari in Africa,

00:04:31.080 --> 00:04:32.730
and there's a couple
of guides usually,

00:04:32.730 --> 00:04:33.900
and they've got big guns.

00:04:33.900 --> 00:04:36.950
And they say to the tourists,
please, please, please,

00:04:36.950 --> 00:04:40.310
no matter what happens,
just don't run.

00:04:40.310 --> 00:04:40.830
Why?

00:04:40.830 --> 00:04:43.770
Because everything scary out
there is faster than you are.

00:04:43.770 --> 00:04:46.170
You see that half
blind hippopotamus--

00:04:46.170 --> 00:04:49.470
I mean that half blind
rhinoceros behind those trees?

00:04:49.470 --> 00:04:51.380
38 miles an hour.

00:04:51.380 --> 00:04:53.450
That big lumbering
hippopotamus in the mud

00:04:53.450 --> 00:04:55.460
puddle-- 42 miles an hour.

00:04:55.460 --> 00:04:58.790
And furthermore, if you run,
everything that's a predator

00:04:58.790 --> 00:05:01.310
is going to think you're prey,
and it'll make matters worse.

00:05:01.310 --> 00:05:03.320
So she couldn't escape.

00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:04.980
She had reasonable
sight-- not as

00:05:04.980 --> 00:05:08.820
good as an eagle or a giraffe,
but better than the rhino.

00:05:08.820 --> 00:05:10.330
Reasonable hearing.

00:05:10.330 --> 00:05:11.520
A lousy sense of smell.

00:05:11.520 --> 00:05:12.970
Just ask your dog.

00:05:12.970 --> 00:05:15.130
How does she possibly make it?

00:05:15.130 --> 00:05:18.150
Well, she basically had a
few things going for her.

00:05:18.150 --> 00:05:20.040
She had a fight or
flight system that

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:22.390
was capable of
emergency response,

00:05:22.390 --> 00:05:25.070
and this was inherited
first from reptiles

00:05:25.070 --> 00:05:27.610
and refined more by mammals.

00:05:27.610 --> 00:05:31.460
And she also had, on top of
that, a prehensile thumb,

00:05:31.460 --> 00:05:33.810
an opposable thumb
that could pick up

00:05:33.810 --> 00:05:36.216
objects, which was really,
really good for using tools.

00:05:36.216 --> 00:05:38.340
And if you've ever seen
your dog try to use a tool,

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:41.930
you understand how useful
it is to have a thumb.

00:05:41.930 --> 00:05:43.660
And the other thing
that she had was she

00:05:43.660 --> 00:05:47.600
had a capacity for thinking--
for thinking about the past,

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:50.900
analyzing what had happened, and
projecting it into the future.

00:05:50.900 --> 00:05:54.580
And it's this third capacity
that helped her enormously

00:05:54.580 --> 00:05:58.340
and also gets us into
a lot of trouble,

00:05:58.340 --> 00:06:00.360
because it turns out
with this ability

00:06:00.360 --> 00:06:02.600
to analyze the past
for pleasure and pain,

00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:04.790
and try to maximize
future pleasure,

00:06:04.790 --> 00:06:08.450
and avoid future pain, isn't
some kind of neutral computing

00:06:08.450 --> 00:06:09.700
apparatus.

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:11.320
It's actually
subject to something

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:12.620
called the negativity bias.

00:06:12.620 --> 00:06:16.146
This is how cognitive
scientists refer to it.

00:06:16.146 --> 00:06:18.020
If you think of Lucy's
predicament out there,

00:06:18.020 --> 00:06:20.100
she could've made one
of two kinds of errors,

00:06:20.100 --> 00:06:22.000
and we could think
of these as a type 1

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.600
and a type 2 error, kind of
analogous to the same kind

00:06:24.600 --> 00:06:27.160
of errors that we use
in scientific research.

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:31.870
She could've looked at a bush
with a beige shape behind it,

00:06:31.870 --> 00:06:34.830
and think, oh, my god, it's
a lion, when it was really

00:06:34.830 --> 00:06:36.284
just a beige rock.

00:06:36.284 --> 00:06:37.950
Or she could've looked
at the same shape

00:06:37.950 --> 00:06:41.510
and said, eh, it's a beige
rock, when it was really a lion.

00:06:41.510 --> 00:06:44.970
Now Lucy could have made
thousands of type 1 errors

00:06:44.970 --> 00:06:48.010
and still lived to
propagate her DNA,

00:06:48.010 --> 00:06:50.730
but if she made just
one type 2 error, that's

00:06:50.730 --> 00:06:52.110
the end of her DNA line.

00:06:52.110 --> 00:06:55.650
So we developed minds and
brains that are really, really

00:06:55.650 --> 00:06:57.600
good at these type 1 errors.

00:06:57.600 --> 00:06:59.780
Our minds, as my friend
Rick Hansen puts it,

00:06:59.780 --> 00:07:01.880
are like Velcro
for bad experiences

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:03.830
and Teflon for good ones.

00:07:03.830 --> 00:07:06.440
Anything bad that happens
in our life sticks.

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:09.140
The good ones slide
right off the pan.

00:07:09.140 --> 00:07:11.730
If you meet with your
boss for a review,

00:07:11.730 --> 00:07:14.590
and you hear about nine things
that you're doing great,

00:07:14.590 --> 00:07:17.616
and your boss tells you about
one area of insufficiency,

00:07:17.616 --> 00:07:19.990
what are you going to think
about at 3:00 in the morning?

00:07:19.990 --> 00:07:22.252
It's not the nine things
that you're doing so well.

00:07:22.252 --> 00:07:23.960
And there are countless
examples of this.

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:25.910
Even other animals do it.

00:07:25.910 --> 00:07:29.000
If you run a rat through a
maze, and at the end of a given

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:32.110
pathway, give it some food, it's
got to go through that trial

00:07:32.110 --> 00:07:34.310
several times to
learn the pathway.

00:07:34.310 --> 00:07:36.970
If at the end, you give it
an electric shock, one trial

00:07:36.970 --> 00:07:40.100
learning, that's all it
needs, and it remembers this.

00:07:40.100 --> 00:07:41.920
Even in couples,
there are people--

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:45.570
there's a couple
of psychologists

00:07:45.570 --> 00:07:47.600
by the last name of Gottman
in the Seattle area,

00:07:47.600 --> 00:07:49.070
and they study couples.

00:07:49.070 --> 00:07:51.220
And they find that
on average, we

00:07:51.220 --> 00:07:54.560
need five warm and fuzzy
interactions with a partner

00:07:54.560 --> 00:07:58.230
to undo the loss of trust
that comes from one fight.

00:07:58.230 --> 00:08:01.550
So the mind has this very
strong negativity bias.

00:08:01.550 --> 00:08:06.536
We can try a little experiment
here just to test this out.

00:08:06.536 --> 00:08:08.160
It may-- we'll see
how this works given

00:08:08.160 --> 00:08:09.860
the current political climate.

00:08:09.860 --> 00:08:12.280
But I'm going to
say two words, and I

00:08:12.280 --> 00:08:14.470
want you to notice the
very first words that

00:08:14.470 --> 00:08:16.970
come to your mind after
I say those two words.

00:08:16.970 --> 00:08:17.920
Ready?

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:21.204
Here are the two
words-- Bill Clinton.

00:08:21.204 --> 00:08:21.870
What do you get?

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:26.030
What came to mind?

00:08:26.030 --> 00:08:28.280
Don't be shy.

00:08:28.280 --> 00:08:29.420
What?

00:08:29.420 --> 00:08:30.190
AUDIENCE: Scandal.

00:08:30.190 --> 00:08:31.023
RON SIEGEL: Scandal.

00:08:31.023 --> 00:08:33.150
Anybody get Monica, for example?

00:08:33.150 --> 00:08:33.650
Yes.

00:08:33.650 --> 00:08:34.360
Blue dress.

00:08:34.360 --> 00:08:34.860
Scandal.

00:08:34.860 --> 00:08:35.794
Something like that.

00:08:35.794 --> 00:08:37.669
That's still what comes
to many of our minds,

00:08:37.669 --> 00:08:39.690
even though, obviously,
his wife is running

00:08:39.690 --> 00:08:41.490
for office at the moment.

00:08:41.490 --> 00:08:45.551
Now whatever you think of
his presidency or politics,

00:08:45.551 --> 00:08:48.050
I mean, he helped resolve the
conflicts in Northern Ireland.

00:08:48.050 --> 00:08:49.460
It was a period of prosperity.

00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:52.530
The fact that what we remember
from this is Monica Lewinsky

00:08:52.530 --> 00:08:55.490
shows you how easy it is
for the negativity bias

00:08:55.490 --> 00:08:56.880
to grab hold of something.

00:08:56.880 --> 00:08:57.970
Scandals stick.

00:08:57.970 --> 00:08:59.680
Loss of trust sticks.

00:08:59.680 --> 00:09:00.870
Bad experiences stick.

00:09:04.370 --> 00:09:06.800
It gets worse.

00:09:06.800 --> 00:09:09.590
It turns out that life is
difficult for everybody,

00:09:09.590 --> 00:09:13.250
in part, because we have
trouble with change.

00:09:13.250 --> 00:09:16.214
This starts very, very early.

00:09:16.214 --> 00:09:17.630
I don't want to
give up my diapers

00:09:17.630 --> 00:09:19.860
and start to use the potty.

00:09:19.860 --> 00:09:22.264
The current arrangement
suits me just fine.

00:09:22.264 --> 00:09:22.930
Are you kidding?

00:09:22.930 --> 00:09:25.810
School with all those strange
people and that weird person

00:09:25.810 --> 00:09:26.602
called the teacher?

00:09:26.602 --> 00:09:27.435
I'm not going there.

00:09:27.435 --> 00:09:28.980
I want to stay home
with mom and dad.

00:09:28.980 --> 00:09:31.188
Now maybe there's some
excitement about these things,

00:09:31.188 --> 00:09:32.994
but there's often a
lot of reluctance.

00:09:32.994 --> 00:09:34.410
I remember, I have
twin daughters.

00:09:34.410 --> 00:09:36.800
They're actually my strongest
meditation teachers.

00:09:36.800 --> 00:09:41.424
And I remember when
they were born,

00:09:41.424 --> 00:09:43.840
and we thought, well, we've
got to do something practical.

00:09:43.840 --> 00:09:46.411
I'd better give up my Toyota
Corolla and get a minivan.

00:09:46.411 --> 00:09:47.660
I didn't think it was so cool.

00:09:47.660 --> 00:09:49.590
I wasn't embracing the change.

00:09:49.590 --> 00:09:52.020
18 years later, they're
ready to go off to college,

00:09:52.020 --> 00:09:53.430
and I went into mourning.

00:09:53.430 --> 00:09:55.590
I thought, now after
18 years of trying

00:09:55.590 --> 00:09:57.200
to form a good
relationship with them

00:09:57.200 --> 00:09:58.870
and be a caring,
loving dad, they're

00:09:58.870 --> 00:10:01.630
going to abandon me like
other girls did when I was 18?

00:10:01.630 --> 00:10:03.354
Who wrote this script?

00:10:03.354 --> 00:10:05.270
My wife, luckily, has a
little bit more wisdom

00:10:05.270 --> 00:10:07.494
about these matters than
I did, and she points out,

00:10:07.494 --> 00:10:09.660
had they been so impaired
that they couldn't go off,

00:10:09.660 --> 00:10:11.040
I'd even more upset.

00:10:11.040 --> 00:10:13.080
But change is hard.

00:10:13.080 --> 00:10:16.210
And as I projected forward, I'm
getting to be an old guy now,

00:10:16.210 --> 00:10:18.634
and imagined entering
assisted living,

00:10:18.634 --> 00:10:20.050
even if they're
playing the Stones

00:10:20.050 --> 00:10:21.980
for my entire
generation, I don't

00:10:21.980 --> 00:10:24.267
think I'm going to
embrace the change.

00:10:24.267 --> 00:10:24.850
How about you?

00:10:24.850 --> 00:10:26.950
Has anybody noticed any
changes in their body

00:10:26.950 --> 00:10:29.140
since you were 20?

00:10:29.140 --> 00:10:31.710
Have you welcomed and
embraced them all?

00:10:31.710 --> 00:10:33.510
This is a hard road.

00:10:36.700 --> 00:10:37.700
There's another problem.

00:10:43.011 --> 00:10:45.510
One of the other things we see
when we go to an African game

00:10:45.510 --> 00:10:48.600
park, and it actually gets
a little bit repetitive,

00:10:48.600 --> 00:10:51.560
because in species after
species, the story is the same.

00:10:51.560 --> 00:10:53.980
There's the dominant
male hanging around

00:10:53.980 --> 00:10:56.326
with the reproductively
promising females,

00:10:56.326 --> 00:10:57.950
and then there's
another group of males

00:10:57.950 --> 00:11:00.810
who are younger doing the
species equivalent of playing

00:11:00.810 --> 00:11:05.040
basketball, honing
their skills and tools,

00:11:05.040 --> 00:11:07.720
getting ready to be able to try
to topple the dominant male.

00:11:07.720 --> 00:11:11.950
And we see this in species
after species after species.

00:11:11.950 --> 00:11:16.030
In humans, this concern
for position in the tribe

00:11:16.030 --> 00:11:20.640
or in the pack is expressed
as a concern for self-esteem.

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:22.050
If you examine
your minds, and we

00:11:22.050 --> 00:11:24.110
get to do this with
mindfulness practices,

00:11:24.110 --> 00:11:26.140
we start to see that
our minds are constantly

00:11:26.140 --> 00:11:28.190
comparing ourselves to others.

00:11:28.190 --> 00:11:30.690
And we choose many,
many different domains

00:11:30.690 --> 00:11:31.970
and dimensions for this.

00:11:31.970 --> 00:11:33.980
For one person, it's
who's wealthier.

00:11:33.980 --> 00:11:36.080
For someone else,
it's who's smarter.

00:11:36.080 --> 00:11:38.914
For another person, who's
got the higher rank position.

00:11:38.914 --> 00:11:41.080
For someone else, it's who's
got the better physique

00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:42.630
or is better athletically.

00:11:42.630 --> 00:11:43.620
Who's thinner?

00:11:43.620 --> 00:11:44.920
Who's more attractive?

00:11:44.920 --> 00:11:46.130
Who's more creative?

00:11:46.130 --> 00:11:47.660
Who has more friends?

00:11:47.660 --> 00:11:48.750
Who is more loved?

00:11:48.750 --> 00:11:50.995
The list goes on and on and on.

00:11:50.995 --> 00:11:52.620
If you hang out with
meditators the way

00:11:52.620 --> 00:11:53.910
I do, it gets really funny.

00:11:53.910 --> 00:11:55.810
Who makes fewer comparisons?

00:11:55.810 --> 00:11:57.850
Who's less self-focused?

00:11:57.850 --> 00:12:00.360
Who sees the bigger
picture better?

00:12:00.360 --> 00:12:03.430
But it's all the
same kind of thing.

00:12:03.430 --> 00:12:05.500
Now assuming you
guys are like me,

00:12:05.500 --> 00:12:08.520
and your minds make these kinds
of comparisons, any of you

00:12:08.520 --> 00:12:10.452
always win?

00:12:10.452 --> 00:12:11.910
I once asked a
group that question,

00:12:11.910 --> 00:12:14.540
and a guy raised his hand, and
I thought, avoid him at lunch.

00:12:14.540 --> 00:12:15.971
Bad sign, right?

00:12:15.971 --> 00:12:16.470
Of course.

00:12:16.470 --> 00:12:18.640
We win some and we lose some.

00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:22.130
And the problem is unless
we live in Lake Wobegon,

00:12:22.130 --> 00:12:25.040
where all the women are strong,
the men are good-looking,

00:12:25.040 --> 00:12:27.390
and every child
is above average,

00:12:27.390 --> 00:12:29.810
we're always going to be
going up and then with this.

00:12:29.810 --> 00:12:33.050
We're constantly, constantly
faced with disappointment

00:12:33.050 --> 00:12:35.270
and sense of failure
and sense of inadequacy,

00:12:35.270 --> 00:12:37.020
because it's
absolutely impossible

00:12:37.020 --> 00:12:38.670
to stay on top all the time.

00:12:38.670 --> 00:12:40.880
Even if you're a gold
medalist in the Olympics,

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:43.120
four years later, you're
probably dethroned,

00:12:43.120 --> 00:12:46.560
and if not then, eight
years later for sure.

00:12:46.560 --> 00:12:52.740
Now to make matters even worse,
who here is going to die?

00:12:52.740 --> 00:12:54.360
That's about 20% of
the hands went up.

00:12:54.360 --> 00:12:56.330
That's a pretty
aware group, right?

00:12:56.330 --> 00:12:59.500
So we have this really
bad predicament.

00:12:59.500 --> 00:13:02.900
We're very, very focused
on who we are, how we seem,

00:13:02.900 --> 00:13:04.810
how we're doing.

00:13:04.810 --> 00:13:07.210
There's all this change
going on, and in the end,

00:13:07.210 --> 00:13:08.850
we fall apart and die.

00:13:08.850 --> 00:13:11.810
It's no wonder that we have a
lot of psychological distress.

00:13:14.640 --> 00:13:16.680
So what I'd like to
do is focus in on some

00:13:16.680 --> 00:13:18.870
of these particular
psychological disorders

00:13:18.870 --> 00:13:21.710
and the most common
ones, and I want

00:13:21.710 --> 00:13:25.200
to do this by discussing a
little bit of a battle that

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:29.200
went on in the American
Psychiatric Association

00:13:29.200 --> 00:13:31.760
when they were
formulating the DSM-5.

00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:33.830
The DSM is the Diagnostic
and Statistical

00:13:33.830 --> 00:13:36.000
Manual of the American
Psychiatric Association.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.400
It's basically the code
book for classifying

00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:41.340
different kinds of psychological
and psychiatric problems.

00:13:41.340 --> 00:13:44.040
And there was this battle when
they were designing the newest

00:13:44.040 --> 00:13:48.560
copy between what we might call
the lumpers and the splitters.

00:13:48.560 --> 00:13:51.430
The splitters said, what was
wrong with the old system was

00:13:51.430 --> 00:13:53.460
we just didn't yet have
a sufficient number

00:13:53.460 --> 00:13:54.970
of diagnostic categories.

00:13:54.970 --> 00:13:58.890
We were still inadvertently
combining apples and oranges.

00:13:58.890 --> 00:14:01.290
The lumpers said, you
know, that's crazy.

00:14:01.290 --> 00:14:03.170
It doesn't really
fit my experience.

00:14:03.170 --> 00:14:05.870
In fact, as a clinician,
for example, I rarely

00:14:05.870 --> 00:14:08.012
see a person with
a single diagnosis.

00:14:08.012 --> 00:14:09.470
Almost everybody's
got a little bit

00:14:09.470 --> 00:14:12.390
of this, a little bit of that,
something of a third diagnosis,

00:14:12.390 --> 00:14:14.840
and in fact, it changes
from week to week.

00:14:14.840 --> 00:14:17.350
They said, you know, I think
if you create more categories,

00:14:17.350 --> 00:14:19.830
you're going to miss the
forest for the trees.

00:14:19.830 --> 00:14:24.170
The splitters, at this point,
naturally said, what forest?

00:14:24.170 --> 00:14:25.690
The lumper said,
well, for example,

00:14:25.690 --> 00:14:28.100
you're not going to see
any of the universals

00:14:28.100 --> 00:14:30.120
in human psychological
difficulties.

00:14:30.120 --> 00:14:31.920
You'll not see the
kinds of problems

00:14:31.920 --> 00:14:34.290
that cut across these
different categories.

00:14:34.290 --> 00:14:35.230
They said universals?

00:14:35.230 --> 00:14:36.396
These are separate diseases.

00:14:36.396 --> 00:14:38.160
They're like syphilis
and a broken bone.

00:14:38.160 --> 00:14:39.980
What's the universals there?

00:14:39.980 --> 00:14:43.480
Well, the lumpers say, for
example, one really powerful

00:14:43.480 --> 00:14:47.450
universal is what we might
call emotional or experiential

00:14:47.450 --> 00:14:48.705
avoidance.

00:14:48.705 --> 00:14:52.290
And let me give you an
idea of how this works.

00:14:52.290 --> 00:14:56.040
Have any of you
ever drunk alcohol?

00:14:56.040 --> 00:14:57.240
Come on.

00:14:57.240 --> 00:14:58.510
20% again?

00:14:58.510 --> 00:14:59.480
Thank you.

00:14:59.480 --> 00:15:01.270
That's a little
bit more realistic.

00:15:01.270 --> 00:15:03.232
Now I know I'm in
California, so some of you

00:15:03.232 --> 00:15:04.930
are going to claim
this, but who does it

00:15:04.930 --> 00:15:08.370
exclusively for the taste?

00:15:08.370 --> 00:15:08.870
Nobody.

00:15:08.870 --> 00:15:10.670
Very honest group.

00:15:10.670 --> 00:15:12.310
Most of us, when
we drink alcohol,

00:15:12.310 --> 00:15:14.990
we do it because we'd like
to change one state of mind

00:15:14.990 --> 00:15:16.950
into a somewhat different state.

00:15:16.950 --> 00:15:18.620
Let's say we've had
a hard day at work,

00:15:18.620 --> 00:15:19.994
and we're feeling
a little tense,

00:15:19.994 --> 00:15:22.530
and muscularly we're
kind of like this.

00:15:22.530 --> 00:15:25.400
And we think, you know, a
beer or a glass of wine--

00:15:25.400 --> 00:15:26.230
that would help.

00:15:26.230 --> 00:15:27.920
I'd feel a little
bit more mellow.

00:15:27.920 --> 00:15:29.704
Or we're going to go
to a party, and there

00:15:29.704 --> 00:15:32.120
are going to be some people
there we don't know, or worse,

00:15:32.120 --> 00:15:34.411
there are going to be some
people there who we do know.

00:15:34.411 --> 00:15:36.530
And we think, you know,
a drink would just

00:15:36.530 --> 00:15:40.266
make this go a little
bit more smoothly.

00:15:40.266 --> 00:15:41.640
So generally, we
drink because we

00:15:41.640 --> 00:15:44.890
want to change one state
into a different state,

00:15:44.890 --> 00:15:48.030
a tense or anxious or unpleasant
state into a more pleasant one.

00:15:48.030 --> 00:15:51.180
And of course, if we do that
from time to time, no problem.

00:15:51.180 --> 00:15:54.140
But if we do that compulsively
and a lot, and in fact,

00:15:54.140 --> 00:15:56.570
can't face life situations
without doing it,

00:15:56.570 --> 00:15:59.400
well, then we have a
substance abuse problem.

00:15:59.400 --> 00:16:01.430
Let's take another
common problem.

00:16:01.430 --> 00:16:03.820
Let's take anxiety.

00:16:03.820 --> 00:16:06.440
If I get nervous before
speaking at Google,

00:16:06.440 --> 00:16:08.880
or I get nervous before
flying in airplanes,

00:16:08.880 --> 00:16:11.620
but I fly in airplanes,
and I speak at Google,

00:16:11.620 --> 00:16:13.010
I don't have an
anxiety disorder.

00:16:13.010 --> 00:16:15.120
I'm just a kind of nervous guy.

00:16:15.120 --> 00:16:17.800
If however, I avoid
public speaking,

00:16:17.800 --> 00:16:20.250
or I won't fly in
a plane, because I

00:16:20.250 --> 00:16:24.030
want to not feel anxious,
that's the pathway

00:16:24.030 --> 00:16:25.290
to an anxiety disorder.

00:16:25.290 --> 00:16:27.180
And that can spread
to all sorts of things

00:16:27.180 --> 00:16:28.850
that we wind up
avoiding, because we're

00:16:28.850 --> 00:16:32.270
trying not to feel the anxiety.

00:16:32.270 --> 00:16:36.750
There was an astronaut, one
of the early space-goers

00:16:36.750 --> 00:16:38.626
who was being
interviewed by an actor,

00:16:38.626 --> 00:16:40.750
because the actor was going
to play him in a movie,

00:16:40.750 --> 00:16:43.220
and he wanted to do a
faithful job of this.

00:16:43.220 --> 00:16:46.090
And the actor said,
I don't get it.

00:16:46.090 --> 00:16:48.050
How do you possibly
have the courage

00:16:48.050 --> 00:16:50.130
to go up in those
untested rockets?

00:16:50.130 --> 00:16:52.310
I would've been terrified.

00:16:52.310 --> 00:16:55.700
And the actor said, I think
you're misunderstanding.

00:16:55.700 --> 00:16:59.770
Courage isn't about
not being terrified.

00:16:59.770 --> 00:17:00.660
We were terrified.

00:17:00.660 --> 00:17:03.035
We had no idea if the things
were going to hold together.

00:17:03.035 --> 00:17:05.599
Courage is about doing
what it makes sense to do,

00:17:05.599 --> 00:17:08.060
even as you feel the fear.

00:17:08.060 --> 00:17:11.099
So we see that emotional
or experiential avoidance,

00:17:11.099 --> 00:17:13.630
trying not to feel
anxious is actually

00:17:13.630 --> 00:17:15.947
at the heart of
anxiety disorders.

00:17:15.947 --> 00:17:16.780
Let's take one more.

00:17:16.780 --> 00:17:19.410
Let's look at
depression a little bit.

00:17:19.410 --> 00:17:21.251
Now all of us, even
if you've never

00:17:21.251 --> 00:17:23.000
been to a therapist
or anything like that,

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:26.869
have sometimes been sad, and
sometimes we felt depressed.

00:17:26.869 --> 00:17:28.650
What in your experience
is the difference?

00:17:28.650 --> 00:17:31.410
How does it feel
differently, qualitatively

00:17:31.410 --> 00:17:33.760
to be sad or depressed?

00:17:33.760 --> 00:17:35.260
Don't be shy about this.

00:17:35.260 --> 00:17:38.970
Everybody knows we've all
experienced these things.

00:17:38.970 --> 00:17:41.274
Anybody want to offer a
difference between sadness

00:17:41.274 --> 00:17:42.690
and how that feels
and depression?

00:17:46.634 --> 00:17:48.610
AUDIENCE: Depression
has more hopelessness.

00:17:48.610 --> 00:17:50.010
RON SIEGEL: Depression
has more hopelessness.

00:17:50.010 --> 00:17:50.509
Absolutely.

00:17:50.509 --> 00:17:52.880
It's got this thought that
it's never going to end.

00:17:52.880 --> 00:17:54.410
Absolutely.

00:17:54.410 --> 00:17:55.700
AUDIENCE: Unenthusiastic.

00:17:55.700 --> 00:17:57.908
RON SIEGEL: Unenthusiastic
in depression, and there's

00:17:57.908 --> 00:18:01.490
a kind of we're cut off
from life engagement,

00:18:01.490 --> 00:18:04.210
from interests, right?

00:18:04.210 --> 00:18:04.745
What else?

00:18:04.745 --> 00:18:06.370
AUDIENCE: Maybe like
a localized to one

00:18:06.370 --> 00:18:08.670
experience versus
pervading the rest of--

00:18:08.670 --> 00:18:10.530
RON SIEGEL: Yeah, often
sadness is poignant.

00:18:10.530 --> 00:18:11.488
It's kind of localized.

00:18:11.488 --> 00:18:13.590
We're sad about something,
and often depression

00:18:13.590 --> 00:18:15.500
is much broader than that.

00:18:15.500 --> 00:18:19.890
And it's kind of our whole life
feels sort of empty or dead.

00:18:19.890 --> 00:18:22.250
Anybody, one more?

00:18:22.250 --> 00:18:25.310
So one way you could think of
this, and one of the features

00:18:25.310 --> 00:18:29.450
that to my mind cuts to the
chase of it, is in depression,

00:18:29.450 --> 00:18:32.550
we feel kind of dead
and kind of shut down,

00:18:32.550 --> 00:18:34.970
whereas in sadness, it's
about a given object.

00:18:34.970 --> 00:18:35.875
We're kind of alive.

00:18:35.875 --> 00:18:38.380
We're kind of still
engaged in life.

00:18:38.380 --> 00:18:41.670
When Shakespeare wrote,
parting is such sweet sorrow,

00:18:41.670 --> 00:18:42.670
we get it.

00:18:42.670 --> 00:18:45.350
Had he written, parting is such
sweet depression, we'd think,

00:18:45.350 --> 00:18:47.560
this guy doesn't
know how to write.

00:18:47.560 --> 00:18:49.250
That wouldn't speak to us.

00:18:49.250 --> 00:18:51.730
So we can see that even in
something like depression,

00:18:51.730 --> 00:18:54.360
there's a kind of shutting
down of the organism.

00:18:54.360 --> 00:18:57.340
There's a kind of closing
down and avoiding experience,

00:18:57.340 --> 00:18:59.690
which is part of this.

00:18:59.690 --> 00:19:05.010
So there's a very nice little
video that is, to my mind,

00:19:05.010 --> 00:19:07.020
a wonderful visual
metaphor for this,

00:19:07.020 --> 00:19:08.910
which I'd like to show to you.

00:19:08.910 --> 00:19:10.910
It's very brief,
but it gives you

00:19:10.910 --> 00:19:16.990
a sense of how this
plays out and, frankly,

00:19:16.990 --> 00:19:22.610
how experiential avoidance
winds up multiplying our misery.

00:19:29.498 --> 00:19:32.942
