01:02:26.020 --> 01:02:27.600
AUDIENCE: I'll ask,
how long do you

01:02:27.600 --> 01:02:32.520
think the average Googler
would need to start practicing

01:02:32.520 --> 01:02:35.380
mindfulness before they start to
see a difference in themselves?

01:02:35.380 --> 01:02:36.838
RON SIEGEL: Well,
it's interesting.

01:02:36.838 --> 01:02:38.430
When Jon Kabat-Zinn
set up a program

01:02:38.430 --> 01:02:40.430
called mindfulness-based
stress reduction, which

01:02:40.430 --> 01:02:47.880
was one of the first programs
to package mindfulness practice

01:02:47.880 --> 01:02:50.420
and disseminate it
to secular audiences

01:02:50.420 --> 01:02:52.430
and to use it in
the medical world,

01:02:52.430 --> 01:02:54.260
he, in that eight-week
training program,

01:02:54.260 --> 01:02:56.810
asked people to do
about 45 minutes a day.

01:02:56.810 --> 01:03:00.510
So fairly intense
commitment, and if you

01:03:00.510 --> 01:03:02.719
do that over the
course of eight weeks,

01:03:02.719 --> 01:03:05.010
you get these profound changes
in brain function, brain

01:03:05.010 --> 01:03:06.600
structure, you really feel it.

01:03:06.600 --> 01:03:08.850
Now some people aren't going
to be willing to do that.

01:03:08.850 --> 01:03:10.780
I find that,
personally, I notice

01:03:10.780 --> 01:03:13.600
I'm doing better if I can
devote 20 minutes a day

01:03:13.600 --> 01:03:15.532
compared to not
doing the practice.

01:03:15.532 --> 01:03:17.490
And there have been a
number of studies showing

01:03:17.490 --> 01:03:20.550
that relatively small doses
over relatively short periods

01:03:20.550 --> 01:03:22.830
of time still have
effects, but this stuff

01:03:22.830 --> 01:03:26.050
does tend to be dose-related,
and the more time, the more

01:03:26.050 --> 01:03:28.120
profound the effects tend to be.

01:03:28.120 --> 01:03:31.240
AUDIENCE: So I've done a little
bit of this sort of meditation

01:03:31.240 --> 01:03:34.990
and kind of trying to be with
the thoughts but not interact,

01:03:34.990 --> 01:03:38.630
and what I find is that either
I'm completely carried away

01:03:38.630 --> 01:03:41.280
with it, or I go
back to this reflex

01:03:41.280 --> 01:03:42.925
where I just disengage
and disconnect.

01:03:42.925 --> 01:03:45.570
And I'm interested
in if you have advice

01:03:45.570 --> 01:03:49.310
on how to sort of be with
it, but not get carried in

01:03:49.310 --> 01:03:50.492
and not run.

01:03:50.492 --> 01:03:51.200
RON SIEGEL: Yeah.

01:03:51.200 --> 01:03:56.080
Well, you know, in
the various systems

01:03:56.080 --> 01:03:58.620
of mindfulness
meditation, there are

01:03:58.620 --> 01:04:02.050
different objects of
meditation that are suggested.

01:04:02.050 --> 01:04:05.430
Most of the systems start
with just sensory experiences

01:04:05.430 --> 01:04:09.910
like the breath, like sounds,
like the sights of nature,

01:04:09.910 --> 01:04:14.560
like the sensation of the
body sitting in the chair,

01:04:14.560 --> 01:04:17.650
but one can also then
expand out to mindfulness

01:04:17.650 --> 01:04:21.530
of feeling and mindfulness
of thought, even.

01:04:21.530 --> 01:04:23.800
But it's much harder
to do those until you

01:04:23.800 --> 01:04:25.780
have a pretty strong
base in concentration,

01:04:25.780 --> 01:04:28.900
exactly what you're describing,
because unless the mind

01:04:28.900 --> 01:04:33.890
is accustomed to staying with
a given mental object, as soon

01:04:33.890 --> 01:04:38.810
as it moves into the realm of
thought, it tends to take off.

01:04:38.810 --> 01:04:40.940
So we feel like we've
got two options.

01:04:40.940 --> 01:04:44.960
One is to sort of
ignore thought, or just

01:04:44.960 --> 01:04:46.120
get into thinking.

01:04:46.120 --> 01:04:48.610
So for me, personally,
it's really only

01:04:48.610 --> 01:04:50.740
when I've been
meditating more, and I've

01:04:50.740 --> 01:04:53.630
got a fair bit of
momentum of concentration

01:04:53.630 --> 01:04:56.350
that I pay much attention to
the mindfulness of thought.

01:04:56.350 --> 01:04:58.770
Most the time I stay
at the sensory level,

01:04:58.770 --> 01:05:00.700
but the sensory level
includes emotions

01:05:00.700 --> 01:05:03.000
in the sense that
at the sensory level

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:08.490
comes fear or anger or joy or
sexual interest or sadness,

01:05:08.490 --> 01:05:10.990
because all of these things
begin as bodily events.

01:05:10.990 --> 01:05:13.110
So I can stay at
the sensory level

01:05:13.110 --> 01:05:15.130
and still explore a
lot of experience,

01:05:15.130 --> 01:05:17.320
but I usually choose when
I'm doing the practice

01:05:17.320 --> 01:05:19.680
to not try mindfulness
of thought,

01:05:19.680 --> 01:05:22.442
unless I'm in a retreat setting
where I'm really developing

01:05:22.442 --> 01:05:23.900
a lot of concentration,
because I'm

01:05:23.900 --> 01:05:27.510
sort of meditating for hours at
a time in one form or another.

01:05:27.510 --> 01:05:32.100
And then there's sufficient
awareness and attention

01:05:32.100 --> 01:05:34.584
to be able to see a thought
without getting caught in it.

01:05:34.584 --> 01:05:36.000
But exactly what
you're describing

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:38.180
is what's described
historically over thousands

01:05:38.180 --> 01:05:41.010
of years of people
experimenting with this.

01:05:41.010 --> 01:05:41.510
OK.

01:05:41.510 --> 01:05:43.840
So thank you so much
